# Core Rules — All Agents

Version: 4.0.0 | Updated: 2026-05-13 | Applies to: all agents

## 1. Absolute constraints (NEVER)

- Skip or reorder workflow steps; start a step without explicit human `flowctl approve` of the previous step
- Commit directly to `main` or `master`; self-approve (`flowctl approve` as agent); change scope without PM approval
- Expose secrets, API keys, or credentials in code, logs, or error messages

## 2. Evidence requirements

Every DELIVERABLE claim in a report MUST include verifiable evidence:

```
DELIVERABLE: path/to/file.ts — short description
EVIDENCE: file_exists

DELIVERABLE: API /users endpoint
EVIDENCE: test_output — 12 tests passed (0 failed)

DELIVERABLE: Design mockup
EVIDENCE: figma_url — https://figma.com/...
```

Rules:

- File path deliverable → `flowctl collect` auto-verifies existence. Missing file = UNVERIFIED
- Non-file deliverable → MUST have `EVIDENCE:` with proof (tests, URL, commit hash)
- Missing or UNVERIFIED evidence → PM MUST NOT approve the step

## 3. Code quality gates (before merge)

| Gate | Threshold |
|------|-----------|
| Lint errors | 0 |
| TypeScript strict errors | 0 |
| Test coverage — lines / branches / functions | ≥ 80% / ≥ 75% / ≥ 85% |
| SAST (Critical / High) | 0 |
| Dependency CVEs (CVSS ≥ 9.0) | 0 |
| Secret scan | 0 |
| Cyclomatic complexity | ≤ 10 per function |
| Function length | ≤ 50 lines |

Naming: files kebab-case; classes PascalCase; functions camelCase; DB snake_case; env UPPER_SNAKE_CASE.

## 4. Security & performance (summary)

- Authentication on endpoints (public exceptions explicit); authorization at service layer, not only controller
- Validate all user input at API boundary and again for business rules; parameterized queries only
- Secrets in env / secret manager; rotation plan; different values per environment; no PII in logs (mask)
- PII at rest encrypted; retention policy; GDPR if EU users
- API latency: monitor p50/p95/p99; product may define stricter SLOs. No N+1; paginate list endpoints (default 20, max 100); connection pooling
- Frontend: meet Core Web Vitals targets in product requirements (baseline: LCP under 2.5s, INP under 200ms, CLS under 0.1)

## 5. Step entry (before starting any step)

- [ ] Previous step has valid approval (except Step 1)
- [ ] Prior blockers resolved or formally accepted by PM
- [ ] `flowctl-state.json` reflects prior approval
- [ ] Prior-step artifacts committed
- [ ] Required agents notified

## 6. Definition of done (before requesting approval)

- [ ] Deliverables complete with evidence (Section 2)
- [ ] Relevant tests pass; docs updated
- [ ] `flowctl collect` succeeded; `flowctl gate-check` passes (or formal PM bypass documented)
- [ ] Changes committed with conventional commits
- [ ] Step summary → `templates/step-summary-template.md`
- [ ] Review checklist → `templates/review-checklist-template.md`
- [ ] Approval request → `templates/approval-request-template.md`

## 7. Blockers, scope, parallel work

**Blockers:** detect → report + `flowctl add-blocker` within 2h → owner → workaround if possible → `flowctl resolve-blocker`. Escalation: CRITICAL under 1h | HIGH same day | MEDIUM under 2 days.

**Scope:** Minor (under 2h) Tech Lead | Moderate (2–8h) PM + Tech Lead | Major (over 8h) change request + PM + stakeholders. **Scope freeze** from Step 7: only P1/P2 critical fixes; PM veto on non-critical.

**Parallel streams** (PM + Tech Lead approval): e.g. 2+3 only with API contracts; 4+5 only with approved OpenAPI; QA prep + Step 6 with Tech Lead sign-off. Clear contracts; integration checkpoints ≥ 2×/week; Tech Lead resolves cross-stream conflicts.

## 8. Step-specific constraints

| Step | Key constraint |
|------|----------------|
| 1 | No design/code before requirements; AC in Given/When/Then |
| 2 | Security threat model; DB schema approved before Step 4 |
| 3 | WCAG 2.1 AA; mobile + desktop approved together |
| 4 | Follow approved OpenAPI; no SAST-failing merges |
| 5 | No UI without approved design; a11y before completion |
| 6 | Contract tests before integration tests; error paths tested |
| 7 | No skipped tests without N/A; Critical+High bugs closed before Go/No-Go |
| 8 | Staging stable ≥ 24h; rollback tested before prod |
| 9 | Stakeholder demo; release notes PM-approved; post-release monitoring |

## 9. Emergency procedures

**Production hotfix during active flowctl:** PM decides within 1h to suspend or not → branch `hotfix/{issue}-{desc}` from `main` → DevOps + Tech Lead + devs → expedited QA (2–4h) → merge to `main` and `develop` → resume flowctl.

**Rollback to prior step:** PM formal approval + reason → `flowctl rollback --to step:{N}` or manual state → notify all agents with impact → re-plan timeline.

## 10. Approval gates

| Step | Required approvers |
|------|-------------------|
| 1 | PM + 1 stakeholder |
| 2 | Tech Lead + PM |
| 3 | UI/UX + PM |
| 4 | Tech Lead |
| 5 | Tech Lead + UI/UX |
| 6 | Tech Lead |
| 7 | QA + PM |
| 8 | DevOps + Tech Lead + PM |
| 9 | PM + Tech Lead + stakeholder |

**PM pre-approval:** `flowctl release-dashboard --no-write` → `approval_ready: yes`, `breaker_state: closed` → `flowctl gate-check` PASS (or documented bypass) → `flowctl approve --by "Name"`.

Statuses: APPROVED | APPROVED WITH CONDITIONS (fix within 48h) | REJECTED | DEFERRED (24h info). Timeout: 24h reminder → 48h escalate → 72h PM decision.

## 11. Communication & escalation

```
[AGENT] → [TARGET/ALL]
Priority: CRITICAL | HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW
Subject: …
Body: …
Action required: … / None
```

Tags: `@pm` `@tech-lead` `@backend` `@frontend` `@ui-ux` `@devops` `@qa` — SLAs: CRITICAL under 1h | HIGH under 8h | MEDIUM under 2d | LOW per sprint.

